ANGER MANAGEMENT CHARITY AUCTION
Current high bid: $2600 (at 7:25am MT, 12.9)

A 40” framed canvas of Anger Management has been donated to feature in @freewildhorses' annual Stay Wild charity auction.

Anger Management is a striking black-and-white image of a wild mustang stallion kicking up a dust storm at Sand Wash Basin, Colorado, one month before the majority of wild horses were removed during the September 2021 roundup.

Anger Management won the coveted Natural World & Wildlife Award at the 2022 Sony World Photography Awards and earned 2022 Open Photographer of the Year honors for Scott Wilson, while putting the plight of the American Mustang on an international stage.
 
Anger Management is currently on show at @mopasd (the Museum of Photographic Arts), in San Diego and Gallery 6 in Denver, Colorado, which will host the Stay Wild Denver live event on 9.12.22.
 
The stallion which features in Anger Management remains free in Sand Wash Basin.

*behind the scenes*
TIME WELL SPENT

We tend to do things old school at @gallery6denver 

Cotton rag prints skillfully torn with our signature deckled edge, a traditional artifact of ancient book-making before machines were able to cut paper with a clean edge. 

We like to think of this old-world flaw as a symbol of our modern craft. 

The thick textured paper is hand-mounted on black linen and elevated on invisible floats so your favorite image stands proud in its setting, as it should. 

Adherence takes time and gentle pressure, all coming together the old-fashioned way. We believe a framed cotton rag print from Gallery 6 is worth the wait. 

Image shows a section of the 54” Legacy Limited Edition Triptych by @wilsonaxpe Photography, beautifully framed by Tony Eitzel. 

All proceeds from this Limited Edition of 10 certified Triptychs support wild mustang rescue efforts by @fortheloveofaria in Kiowa, Colorado.

*Breaking News*
2023 Colorado Bill proposes Wild Mustang to be named as the State Horse of Colorado.

A 2023 Bill has been unveiled which plans to make the Wild Mustang the State Horse of Colorado, sponsored by Colorado Sentator Joann Ginal and State Representative Monica Duran. 

The Bill, which also proposes improved on-range management provisions for wild horses in Colorado was unveiled at the Stay Wild Denver event, hosted by @freewildhorses and @wilsonaxpe at Gallery 6 Denver on Friday night (12.9.22)

The Stay Wild event, which featured wild horse artwork by @wilsonaxpe was attended by Colorado Governor Jared Polis, First Gentleman Marlon Reis and Colorado Senators Kerry Donavan and Lucia Guzman, as well as VIPs and guests of the American Wild Horse Campaign.

@govofco Jared Polis spoke of the prominent role wild horses play in Colorado's rich tapestry from the Mustang statue which greets visitors at Denver International Airport to football giants, the Denver Broncos and the world's most famous wild mustang, Picasso, the legend of Sand Wash Basin (shown here).

I will keep you posted as the Bill progress unfolds in the 2023 session.

Colorado Governor and First Gentlemen honor Wild Horses and commend advocates at Stay Wild Denver event. 

I was deeply privileged to welcome @govofco Colorado Governor Jared Polis, @firstgentmarlonreis, VIPs and guests of the American Wild Horse Campaign (@freewildhorses) to Gallery 6 in @denversartdistrict last night for a celebration of the prominent role that wild horses play in the Colorado tapestry and natural environment.

Both the Governor and First Gentleman have shown tremendous leadership and commitment to pursue a better way for wild horse management through humane and effective long term conservation and were incredibly gracious in commending the work of wild horse advocates in Colorado in their formal remarks to guests at the event. 

I was thrilled to present a framed print of Merlin and the Foal to the Governor and First Gentleman in gratitude for their continued efforts to preserve Colorado’s wild horses, as well as a framed print of Reis, the newborn foal I named in the First Gentleman’s honor, in May of this year.

More Stay Wild Denver news and updates to follow.

I love seeing an art lover’s personal vision come to life.

This particular client wanted to capture her love of Colorado’s wild horses and the incomparable fall landscapes that bring visitors from all over the world during autumn.

After browsing hundreds of Colorado nature and landscape print options at Gallery 6, we settled on a triptych featuring the Painted Ladies of Sand Wash Basin straddled by fall scenes from Last Dollar Road and Ridgeway in southwest Colorado. 

Each 16” image is printed on thick cotton rag paper, hand-torn with a deckled edge and mounted on black linen. 

The prints are now just awaiting their bespoke 54” inch frame to complete the triptych, but I couldn’t wait that long to share it!

Another fine art collaboration between @WilsonAxpe and the masterly print & framing skills of Tony Eitzel at Gallery 6 Denver.

IMPRINT Colorado shortlist revealed with Smartphone, Infrared and Cyanotype photography among contest leaders.

A shortlist of six finalists has been announced in the IMPRINT Colorado contest, which will see three Colorado photographers win their own show at Gallery 6 in Denver’s Art District on Santa Fe, during Denver Month of Photography (@mopdenver) in March 2023.

Among the photographers progressing to the final stage of the free-to-enter contest are a smartphone artist from Lakewood, an infrared photographer from Colorado Springs and a cyanotype exponent, from Loveland. 

The shortlist features:
Colleen Hennessy, Denver (@cohennes)
Kent Youngblood, Denver (@youngblood.kent) 
Ed Schlotzhauer, Loveland (www.photos.schlotzcreate.com) - 
Robert Newman, Lakewood (@strayimages) 
Sherri Mabe, Co Springs (@starlitwaltz) 
Cameron Douglas, Fort Collins (@rotten.prints) 

IMPRINT Colorado organizer Scott Wilson (@wilsonaxpe) said: “We knew Colorado had a very high caliber artist community, but still we were blown away by the standard of work entered in our inaugural contest. There’s truly a hair’s breadth between those who made the shortlist and those just outside and we really commend everyone who has taken part.”

Wilson said the gallery’s intention was to provide a platform for undiscovered Colorado talent and to portray the power of photography in print form.

The jury is now locked away for the final round of judging to select three winning photographers, who will each receive a large framed print of their chosen piece - crafted by Colorado craft framer, Tony Eitzel - to kick off their own show at Gallery 6 in Denver’s Art District on Santa Fe during @mopdenver

Colorado Launches Anti Equine Slaughter Bill

Colorado lawmakers Sen. Sonya Jaquez Lewis (D-eastern Boulder County) and Rep. Lorena Garcia (D-Commerce City) have unveiled a new Bill to prevent the killing of horses for human consumption. The bill requires blocking imports and exports of horses for the purpose of slaughter. It would mandate notices at livestock auctions. Violators would face fines of up to $10,000 for fraudulent transactions.

*SB23-038-007-008*
The Importance Of A Bill Title

Once the scope of a Colorado bill title has been narrowed, it cannot be widened and subsequent amendments must comport with the latest bill title. So, SB23-38, which was intended to prohibit equine slaughter for human consumption, can now only impact transport, not slaughter; has no scope to impact transportation loads carrying less than 20 horses to slaughter; and no scope to improve equine transportation to slaughter generally, unless it's intended for human consumption.

CALIFORNIA has an almost identical transportation statute to that proposed for Colorado – relating to ventilation, adequate space, ramps and nonskid surfaces - except that California ALSO has a total ban on equine slaughter for human consumption, so the California statute applies to transportation for equine slaughter in general - much wider than the Colorado Bill title would allow.

In terms of language, NEW YORK has an almost identical equine transportation statute (NY Agric. & Mkts. Law § 359-A) to that proposed for Colorado - indeed much of the Colorado language is simply cut and paste; EXCEPT that the New York statute applies to transportation of SIX or more horses for ANY PURPOSE - benefitting much smaller truckloads of horses than the Colorado Bill would allow

MARCH IS COLORECTAL CANCER AWARENESS MONTH

In 2016, I was diagnosed with Stage 4 colon cancer, aged 48. 

Thanks to world-class surgery, treatment and ongoing care, I’m in remission, but with a 10-14% survival rate (defined as living 5 years past diagnosis) at Stage 4, I am truly one of the lucky ones.

With preventive screening, colorectal cancers are highly avoidable and treatable. Caught early, there is a 90% survival rate, yet 5 out of 10 of people in their 50s who are eligible for preventive screening don’t bother. Well, it’s an old man’s disease, right? 

This "old man’s disease" is the fastest growing young female cancer and the most lethal cancer among men under 50 in the US. 

So, if you are eligible for screening and haven’t yet done so, please use this March to ask yourself why not.

For further information, or help, you can reach out to the good people at the @colorectalcanceralliance

@WilsonAxpe and @gallery6denver are honored to be hosting the inaugural meeting of the Colorado Chapter of the @PSA Photographic Society of America on May 6, in Denver.

Founded in 1934, the PSA and the network of 460 clubs they represent globally are a great way to learn camera craft and meet like-minded artists - regardless of skill or experience level - and to access a healthy global competition circuit, when you feel ready to test your skills.

The Colorado Chapter will be the Society’s 12th US Chapter - following in the founding footsteps of the Chicago Chapter which was formed in 1955 - and promises to provide a welcoming community hub for photographers across the state.

I will deliver a presentation to the inaugural group, focused on my personal journey towards Photo Advocacy, built around the key role that photography can play in supporting communities and causes we believe in.

The inaugural meeting is open to new Chapter Members and existing members of the Colorado PSA. 

If you would like to learn more, or sign up to join the inaugural meeting, please contact Chapter President Deborah Milburn at ddmilburn3@gmail.com

THE COLORADO WILD HORSE PROJECT — New Colorado Bill has the potential to reduce the need for roundups and removals of wild horses by implementing on-range solutions at scale.
 
Colorado Senator Joann Ginal (D), Senator Perry Will (R), House Majority Leader Monica Duran (D) and House Minority Leader Mike Lynch (R) are co-sponsoring a 2023 bill (SB23-275) that would significantly increase investment in wild horse conservation solutions, such as improved habitat management and scale implementation of fertility control.
 
The Bill proposes the creation of The Wild Horse Project comprising on-range and off-range initiatives, including a state-sponsored structure to help co-ordinate and increase humane fertility control within Colorado HMAs (herd management areas) and the formation of an off-range working group focused on improving adoption rates and exploring additional options for off-range preserves.

The Colorado Wild Horse Project

Senate Bill SB23-275 The Colorado Wild Horse Project will be heard by the Senate Agriculture and Natural Resources Committee on Thursday April 20, in Denver.

SB23-275 proposes novel bi-partisan legislation with the potential to reduce the need for removals of wild horses by allocating $1.5m in state funding and full-time resources to expand existing Colorado-based efforts, such as fertility control and on-range stewardship.

Less than 1% of the BLM’s federal wild horse program budget was allocated towards fertility control in 2021.

With federal funds directed towards managing an off-range capacity crisis and inadequate investment in on-range conservation tools, this is Colorado’s best available option to keep more wild horses on the range and help to reduce the traumatic reactive cycle of large-scale helicopter roundups in future years.

The bill also proposes a working group to expand non-lethal off-range solutions, such as increasing responsible adoptions and exploring new off-range preserves.

If you are a Colorado resident, please reach out to the Agriculture and Natural Resources Committee to ask respectfully for their support. Despite claims that there’s a national scramble for the $1.5m grant designated by the bill, the state funds are intended to remain in Colorado in their entirety to support state-based organizations.

I hope the Colorado Wild Horse Project envisaged by Senate Bill 23-275 will become a catalyst for creative legislative solutions and signal a concerted, collaborative effort to reduce roundups and removals by focusing on cost-effective on-range priorities.

The larger opportunity for this type of legislative effort is evident in the publication this week of the summer schedule of federal roundups with close to 6,000 wild horses targeted for removal before fall in the US, but just 1,600 in the plan for fertility treatment.

If we are to finally get ahead of the opportunity for a truly sustainable and tax-efficient program, there has to be a significant switch in priority towards on-range retention, not unaffordable removals. 

Fertility control is demonstrably effective at 70-80% coverage of reproductive mares. 

If we accept, for argument’s sake, that the nation’s herd is 80,000 wild horses, of which approximately 40% (or 32,000) are reproductive mares, a nationwide darting program should be targeting 22,000-25,000 mares, or fifteen times the current plan. 

SB23-275 offers a significant step towards proving a different model will work. Despite claims that there’s a national scramble for the $1.5m grant designated by the bill, the state funds are intended to remain in Colorado in their entirety to support state-based organizations.

NORSE GODS & UNICORNS… A fogbow or ‘white rainbow’ is a special moment to capture in-camera. A lunar fogbow is a still rarer, more elusive sight than its solar counterpart, being nocturnal and fainter to the naked eye, since it’s powered by the moon rather than the sun. I was lucky to catch the unique sight of this white rainbow framing iconic Thor’s Well on the Oregon coast, nearly three hours after sunset. With a mist-subdued three-quarters moon directly behind me, staring over Thor’s Well towards a solid wall of sea haar, the fogbow gently emerged in my viewfinder. At first, I didn’t allow myself to hope I’d caught a fogbow, but imagined there was a refraction of sorts on my ND filter. The phenomenon remained in place without the filter become more visible to the naked eye for a brief moment. Shooting in near pitch dark with sea spray and dripping fog thickening the air, manually focusing wide-open at f/2.8, it’s tough to create a completely clean shot, but I’m thrilled to have had the experience.... #thorswell #thorswelloregon #oregoncoast #fogbow #lunarfogbow #lunarphenomenon #coast #pacificnorthwest #pacificocean #coastaldrama #seascape #nocturne #nocturnallandscape

I’m thrilled to join the contributor team at the world’s leading animal photojournalism agency, We Animals Media (@weanimals)
 
Founded in 2019 by renowned photojournalist, Jo-Anne McArthur, We Animals Media’s not-for-profit mission is to document stories of animals in the human environment and connect those stories to outlets that can amplify their reach.  
 
@weanimals has built an international network of photojournalists, investigating animal industries and assignments in more than 70 countries. I’m full of admiration for the lengths to which these visual storytellers will go to get the word out, whether they are covering the wild and charismatic or deeply focused on farmed, experimented and otherwise exploited animals.
 
I was privileged to meet Jo-Anne McArthur earlier this year, in Denver, when she shared Hidden: Animals in the Anthropocene, an unflinching photo-documentary of the human relationship with non-human animals in the 21st century, depicted through the lenses of 40 award-winning photojournalists.
 
Sincere thanks to Marlon Reis @firstgentlemanmarlonreis, Colorado’s most prominent advocate for animals and artists, for inviting Jo-Anne to Colorado and for making the initial introduction.

CHIP OFF THE OLD BLOCK

Rescued foal StellaLuna, flanked by her grandsire, wild stallion Picasso of Sand Wash Basin, in northwest Colorado.

Now approaching two years old, StellaLuna was separated from her mother in the September 2021 helicopter roundup and subsequently rescued by @fortheloveofaria in Kiowa, Colorado.

The Sanctuary, which cares for around 50 rescued horses, has its annual fundraiser this Saturday 12th August from 4-8pm. 

LEGACY LIMITED EDITION TRIPTYCH

The final edition of Legacy, a limited edition Triptych by @WilsonAxpe, featuring StellaLuna flanked by grand-sire Picasso and her sire Snip is being placed into a special draw giving horse lovers a unique opportunity to win Legacy by way of a $50 donation. 
This charity-only piece has a retail value of $2400.

For every $50 donation during the run up to the event, donors will receive an entry into the draw which I will pull out of the hat as the event closes on the evening of August 12th. 

Only ten editions of Legacy have been created and this is the final opportunity to acquire this special piece, with all proceeds going towards the care of rescued mustangs at the sanctuary. 

You can make $50 donations via PayPal and Zelle: fortheloveofaria19@gmail.com or Venmo via @fortheloveofaria or by mail to For the Love of Aria, PO Box 952 Kiowa, CO 80117

If you have any queries about the draw, please feel free to contact Gina at fortheloveofaria19@gmail.com

When sunflowers mature, they no longer follow the sun, due to the weight of their seeds holding their heads down.

I was recently accused, as I often am, of doctoring an image, in this case it was a field a sunflowers which were all facing me, with the sunset behind them.
